Java Developers Community (moderated)Java Developers Community (moderated) Bharat Patel 3rd+Bharat Patel 3rd+
1d Edited 1d Edited
How does Docker work?

A comparison of Docker-based and non-Docker-based development is shown below.
With Docker, we can develop, package, and run apps quickly:
The developers can write code locally and then build a Docker image and push it to a dev environment. In this way, the development work is shared within the team. The tests are run automatically in the dev env.

An image is a read-only template with instructions for creating a Docker container. We use a Dockerfile to define the steps to create the image and run it.

The above process can run incrementally when bugs are found or improvements are needed.

When dev testing is complete, the Docker image is pushed to the production environment (often on the cloud).

Compared with traditional development without Docker, Docker is quite lightweight and fast, because only the changed part of Dockerfile is rebuilt every time we make a change.

Over to you: Where are Docker images stored?

Source: blog.bytebytego.com

Follow Bharat Patel for more.

Darrell Padgett, MSDarrell Padgett, MS 3rd+ 3rd+ Resilience and Confidence Expert, Speaker, Author, and Narrator at the Obama Oral History Presidential CenterResilience and Confidence Expert, Speaker, Author, and Narrator at the Obama Oral History Presidential Center
1w Edited 1w Edited
I was sentenced to serve 37.5 years in a prison cell based on a law that nearly everyone knew was enacted for the incarceration of Black men and womenthe crack law [discontinued in January of 2023]. After being placed in a prison cell, no one heard my cries for freedom. Thus I realized I was invisible to society. This realization occurred after my family and I had written hundreds of letters to organizations asking for help to no avail.

My maximum release date from prison was in 2031, and I knew I would live or die in a prison cell, except there was one way out! I had to learn to write the English language coherently. Moreover, I had to learn and understand Criminal Law and the logic of persuasive and passive tones. I was a high school dropout, but I had the unwavering confidence that I could learn Criminal Law and use it to fight the U.S. government for my freedom.

For 20 years, I studied Criminal Law while I was incarcerated. For 20 years, I argued with judges in the district courts, judges in the court of appeals, and justices in the U.S. Supreme Court. For 20 years, I counseled my comrades that were in prison. For 20 years, courts routinely denied my requests for freedom. Then one day, a senior United States district court judge issued an immediate release order based on an argument that I presented.

That morning, prison officials informed me they had 60 minutes to release me from custody! My immediate adventure after I was released from prison was to become a college student where I earned several college degrees culminating with a masters degree summa cum laude.

People often ask me how did I do it? Theres a simple explanation. Confidence and resiliency! It is so difficult to get people to believe in themselves when they allow their perception of an endeavor to defeat their confidence. Always believe in yourself and have faith!

#selfconfidence #motivation #alwaysbelieveinyourself #dontgiveup #motivationalspeaker #criminaljustice

Humanity is alive .

Hats off to the guys who save one life

Humanity, also known as humankind or human society, refers to the entire population of human beings on Earth. The term can also be used to refer to the characteristics that define humanity, such as the ability to think, communicate, and create culture.

Regarding animals, humanity has a complex relationship with them. Humans have domesticated many animals for food, transportation, and companionship. However, humans have also caused the extinction of many animal species and continue to negatively impact the environment and biodiversity through activities such as deforestation, pollution, and climate change.

 Top 50 CSS Interview Questions

CSS, or Cascading Style Sheets, is a language used to describe the presentation of a document written in HTML or XML. It is used to style web pages and make them look visually appealing. CSS has become an essential skill for frontend developers.

If you are preparing for a frontend developer interview, it is important to have a good understanding of CSS.

It is recommended to go through online resources that cover CSS fundamentals and also practice CSS exercises on websites such as Codecademy, FreeCodeCamp, W3Schools, and CSS-Tricks. These websites offer interactive exercises and tutorials to help you improve your CSS skills and gain confidence for your interview.

You can learn CSS from the platforms like Codecademy, freeCodeCamp and W3Schools.com

Git Notes: A Quick Reference Guide for Developers

Git is a powerful version control system that is widely used in the software development industry. However, mastering Git can be challenging, especially for beginners. That's where Git Notes come in handy.

Git Notes are a quick reference guide that provides an overview of the most commonly used Git commands and their syntax. They are a handy resource for developers who need to quickly look up a specific command or syntax.

This Git Notes guide covers all the fundamental Git concepts, including creating a new repository, adding files to the repository, committing changes, branching and merging, and working with remote repositories. It also includes tips and tricks for using Git effectively.

Whether you are a beginner or an experienced developer, Git Notes will help you become more productive and efficient in your Git workflow. You can download the Git Notes PDF or refer to the online version whenever you need to refresh your memory on Git commands.

With Git Notes, you will have a valuable resource at your fingertips to help you navigate Git like a pro.
